<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25180a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25180a">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25180a"> 180(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Adamites</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The Montanists in Phrygia in the second century held &ldquo;revivalist&rdquo; meetings exactly like those of the Welsh to-day, or of the Moslems in Persia, and the negroes in America. The immoral meetings of the <mark>Adamites</mark>, among Christians, are indistinguishable from the Bacchic orgies which were forbidden by horror-stricken Romans in 186 B.C., or from the vile rites of existing Sakti sects in India. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 160</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The Adamites were members of an obscure sect, probably extant during the middle of the fourth century, and so-called because they imitated Adamic simplicity in going without clothing while at worship.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14121d" href="c14all.htm#c14121d">VI.C.14:121(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
